  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The lxx renders סוד, κραταίωμα, as though it were equivalent to יסוד. The reciprocal נוסד, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (which see), leads one to the right primary signification. Starting from the primary meaning of the root סד, \"to be or to make tight, firm, compressed,\" סוד signifies a being closely pressed together for the purpose of secret communication and converse, confidential communion or being together, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 111:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Symm. ὁμιλία), then the confidential communication itself, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 55:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a secret (Aquila ἀπόῤῥητον, Theod. μυστήριον). So here: He opens his mind without any reserve, speaks confidentially with those who fear Him; cf. the derivative passage ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 3:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and an example of the thing itself in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 18:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 25:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the infinitive with ל, according to Ges. ֗132, rem. 1, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 38:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is an expression for the fut. periphrast.: faedus suum notum facturus est iis; the position of the words is like ",
